SIMPLE: satiate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Satiate
<hw>Sa"ti*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>satiatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>satiare</ets> to satisfy, from
<ets>sat</ets>, <ets>satis</ets>, enough. See <er>Sad</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>, and cf. <er>Sate</er>.]</ety> <def>Filled to satiety;
glutted; sated; -- followed by <xex>with</xex> or <xex>of</xex>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Satiate</xex> of applause.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Pope.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Satiate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Satiate
<hw>Sa"ti*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Satiated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Satiating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To satisfy
the appetite or desire of; to feed to the full; to furnish enjoyment to,
to the extent of desire; to sate; <as>as, to <ex>satiate</ex> appetite
or sense</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These [smells] rather woo the sense than <qex>satiate</qex>
it.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I may yet survive the malice of my enemies, although they should
be <qex>satiated</qex> with my blood.</q> <rj><qau>Eikon
Basilike.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To full beyond natural desire; to gratify to
repletion or loathing; to surfeit; to glut.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To saturate.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir
I. Newton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To satisfy; sate; suffice; cloy; gorge; overfill;
surfeit; glut.</syn> -- <usage><er>Satiate</er>, <er>Satisfy</er>,
<er>Content</er>. These words differ principally in degree. To
<xex>content</xex> is to make contented, even though every desire or
appetite is not fully gratified. To <xex>satisfy</xex> is to appease
fully the longings of desire. To <xex>satiate</xex> is to fill so
completely that it is not possible to receive or enjoy more; hence, to
overfill; to cause disgust in.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Content</qex> with science in the vale of peace.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His whole felicity is endless strife;⟦br⟧
No peace, no <qex>satisfaction</qex>, crowns his life.</q>
<rj><qau>Beaumont.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He may be <qex>satiated</qex>, but not <qex>satisfied</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Norris.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Satiation</ent>⟦br⟧
